Here is someone who is just repairing my kitchen floor. And I'm pretending I still have a job and working from home while I work on Too Hot to Handle.
If I fucking managed to open the file. (Damn One Drive.)
*Voice of a hacker* I'm in.
And that's when he starts drilling incredibly loud. Hooray.
It feels uncomfortably passive-aggressive to turn the air purifier all the way up, but I can smell the wood dust, so it would even be totally fine if he weren't a mask opponent. Do I really need to protect myself?
I would really like to go back to bed, but I can't do that before he leaves.
At least I finally finished revising Chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but so damn terrifying. Oh yes, that's the good stuff!
I'm doing a search and replace for ... ➡️ ellipsis symbol and there are 54 in this chapter 😅
But no, I stick with it. Natural language is usually fragmented, especially when one becomes emotional.
The handyman is now vacuuming. Hopefully, that means he will be finished soon.
He went out to cut something (that's how it sounds). I secretly checked on him. There's still a lot to do :(
Still 7 pages left in Chapter 5. It's still my favorite chapter and it's quite tidy – mostly changes in the text and very minor corrections in direct speech, and I need to formulate everything a bit more concisely. But I could really use a break and a tea, but the guy is still in my kitchen.
Now he's starting to vacuum again. Hopefully, that's a good sign.
The kitchen guy is gone!
He told me that he would have made a cost estimate for the entire floor, but the landlords were too tight and only paid for the part next to the door that wasn't in order anymore. It feels much better now.
The house is ventilating, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen, while I'm drinking tea in the garden!
